Center: US National Nuclear Data Center, Brookhaven, USA
ref: Jour: Nuclear Science and Engineering, Vol.163, p.1 (2009)
title: The 10B(n,a0)7Li and 10B(n,a1g)7Li alpha-particle angular distributions for En < 1 MeV

x4freetext: The 10B(n,a0)7Li and 10B(n,a1g)7Li alpha-particle
angular distributions for En < 1 MeV

x4codes.hlp: Sofia, Inst. of Nuclear Res. and Nuclear Energy, Bulgaria

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Nuclear Science and Engineering, Vol.163, p.1 (2009)

x4freetext: Experiment performed at the Geel
Electron Linear Accelerator time-of-flight spectrometer
B4C deposit with minimal purity of 98.0% enriched in
B10 to 94.0% with thickness of 14.5(8) and 15.7(8)
mu-g/cm2 and diameter of 84 mm. Two samples of each
thickness were used. B4C deposited on polished
stainless steel foil with thicknes of 0.3mm and
diameter of 100 mm
A twin Frisch-grid gas ionization chamber was
used. With this type of detector, a simultaneous
measurement of the energy and angular distribution
of the charged particles from the reaction is
possible in a nearly 2x2Pi geometry.The two boron
samples were mounted in a back-to-back geometry on the
common cathode of the chamber.
Energy of incident neutrons determined by
time-of-flight
Photoneutrons produced by Bremsstrahlung in
an uranium target. Measurements were performed at
two different flight-path distances from the GELINA
neutron-producing target: L1 = 28.24 m (moderated
beam) and L2 = 57.41 m (unmoderated beam). A B4C
filter was placed in the beam, which effectively
removed neutrons with thermal and epithermal energies.
Corrected for different sample thickness (4%) in
backside ion chamber
Compiled by S.H.
OS. Headings COS, DATA replaced by COS-CM,
DATA-CM in all subentries.
Data presented in figs. 6,7 of the reference
and data for additional angles, sent by author (F.-J.H)
Statistical uncertainty
